[SiliconPkg]

  Revert "Fix an issue about PCH debug SerialIo UART PCI mode"
  
  [Issue Description]
  Unable to see debug prints once FSP debug lib gets control in coreboot.
  
  [Resolution]
  The original patch fix an issue about PCH debug SerialIo UART PCI mode,
  but need FSP-S UART policy setting in SiPolicy.
  But therey is maybe some issue for such setting with coreboot.
  Now remove the support for PCH debug SerialIo UART PCI mode.
  
  This reverts following commit:
  "Fix an issue about PCH debug SerialIo UART PCI mode"
  
  And in FspLpssUartDebugGetDeviceConfig(), does not call
  GetSerialIoConfig() now.

  ClientOneSiliconPkg/Fsp/Library/FspSerialIoUartDebugHelperLib

[ASL]

  [MTL-S][A0][PO] S0ix and Sx.ix Entry blocked due to AON3 and AON3_SPI
  are active
  
  [Feature Description]
  PMC WA on issue "Second PECI over eSPI commands stuck"
  polling with 1ms interval on ESPI SB SPI_MSI_STS_OOB.SMBUS_AVA
  regularly and disable it during s0ix.
  Timer for polling will be enabled at c10 exit,disable during c10 entry.
  wa will inform PMC (through IPC command) to stop polling on S0ix entry.
  On S0ix exit, BIOS will need to inform PMC again to start the polling.
  
  Package/Module:
  EcFeaturePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTL-S
  
  Hsd-es-id: 15012689179
  Change-Id: If1e12c1c154490f44524717ef5e9d086929891c5
  Original commit hash: 522f67292eb0cac53a64547ef47e9b52c4b0f7df
  
  Features/Ec/EcFeaturePkg/AcpiTables/EcSsdt/EcExternalMethod.asl

[PlatformPkg]

  [MTL] Add DC6 Latency WA setup option
  
  [Feature Description]
  Due to a late bug applicable to both SOC A*/B steppings, we need to
  apply a PCODE WA that would limit CDIE CStates based on the TNTE/LTR
  values from a USB device.
  
  The code change adds a new SETUP option
  "DC6 Latency WA" with disabled as default. When enabled, a mailbox
  command is sent to PCODE.
  
  Package/Module: MeteorLakePlatSamplePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTL

[BoardPkg]

  [MTL-S] Change Power meter 1 address from 0x10 to 0x17
  
  [Feature Description]
  The original RVP layout has a conflict:
  The I2C slave address of ANX7498QN conflicts PWR MON1.
  RVP team change PWR MON1 to 0x17, BIOS needs corresponding changes.
  
  Besides, OC RVP does not have power meter on board.
  Remove S05 power meter reporting and the SSDT accordingly.
  
  Package/Module: MeteorLakeBoardPkg

[BoardPkg]

  [Feature Description]

[SiliconPkg], [BoardPkg]

  [MTLS] Refine Pcie clock usage map setting
  
  [Issue Description]
  FIA CLKREQ register on PXPB is incorrect
  Current code to handle Pcie clock usage map is confusing.
  e.g., DMI FIA_P5X16 P0, however DMI is not Pcie RP 0 in PCIE IP.
  
  [Resolution]
  VpdPcdPcieClkUsageMap does not have dedicated definition for DMI.
  Set Clock 0 as FREE_RUNNING and specifically handle DMI case in
  MtlSocInit and FiaSocLibMtl.c.
  Also revert ClockNumber shifting in DisableClockBufferProgramming().
  
  Package/Module:ClientOneSiliconPkg, MeteorLakeBoardPkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTL-S

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-S MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5 LPDDR5] CLK/WCK TCO Comp training causes
  catastrophic MRC failure at 5600/6400
  
  [Feature Description]
  If the CLK/WCK duty cycle is changed, either by TCO comp or DCC params,
  it changes the CLK/WCK edge. A JEDEC reset needs to be run if this
  happens. The MrcWckTcoCompTraining, MrcDccLpddr5Wck,
  MrcClkTcoCompTraining, and MrcDccDdr5Clk training steps will need this.
  Request to also add a param option flag to call MrcResetSequence for any
  training parameter that will need a JEDEC reset.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl
  
  [Impacted Platform]

[BoardPkg], [PlatformPkg]

  [CNV] BIOS to tri-state the I2S/CRF interface per integrated/discrete
  
  [Feature Description]
  During Pre MEM GPIO Init,
  When Discrete Audio Offload is Enabled,
  Program High-Z to the GPP_F_4 (CRF_RESET) and GPP_F_5 (CRF_CLKQ).
  When Discrete Audio Offload is Disabled,
  Program High-Z on I2S signal GPP_D_15 (I2S2SFRM) and GPP_D_16 (I2S_TX).
  
  Package/Module: GPIO
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 16018782127
  Change-Id: I1faa1eba465ff438cd95a1da0ce1cf6ef32716f6

[BoardPkg]

  Refactor UEFI Variable Protection code into Intel/Features folder
  
  [Feature Description]
  Refactor Variable Protection feature code and place it in the
  Intel/Features/ folder. The feature was made more specific
  to Intel platforms. The feature only supports AES-256 encryption.
  The feature supports only 2 RPMC counters. The SALT for key
  generation is now random and obtained from CSME. The code
  flow behavior now matches the legacy Variable driver.

  ProtectedVariablePkg, MeteorLakeBoardPkg

Commit: 206470e5027ede3299ba509336213f29915c8d41 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg], [PlatformPkg]

  [MTL-M MTL-P MTL-S | DDR5 LP5] Add option in BIOS to Enable/Disable
  Memory OppSR
  
  [Feature Description]
  (1) BIOS must provide a setup menu option to Enable/Disable
  Opportunistic Self Refresh
  (2) Opportunistic Self Refresh must be disabled by default
  (3) When the BIOS setup menu Opportunistic Self Refresh is option is
  disabled, BIOS must set POWER_CTL.SAPM_IMC_C2_POLICY = 0
  (4) When the BIOS setup menu Opportunistic Self Refresh is option is
  enabled, BIOS must set POWER_CTL.SAPM_IMC_C2_POLICY = 1
  (5) POWER_CTL.SAPM_IMC_C2_POLICY must be configured after
  MEM_CONFIG_DONE is set and before BIOS_RESET_CPL is set.
  
  Additional Changes:
  - Removed MRC register writes to MC PM_OPP_SREF_ENABLE.Opp_SREF_Enable.
  The state of this CR is controlled by PUNIT during normal operation.
  - Removed unused MEMORY_CONFIGURATION SocStepping field.
  - Changed runtime MRC input struct size and offset checks to compile
  time asserts.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  ALL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 22015434513
  Change-Id: I00cedf1200a77c936d3662ae7cb32b17820c94f0
  Original commit hash: bf5514cdbe254805732af6ebc2fc887acdb0bbfd
  
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl/Include/MrcExtInputs.h

  ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl/LibraryPrivate/PeiMemoryInitLib/Source/Chip/Mc/MrcMcConfiguration.c

[BoardPkg]

  [MTL] VtioSupport Setup Knob variable should be read by using
  mVtioFormSetGuid from GetVariable in AcpiPlatform file
  
  [Issue Description]
  VtioSupport Setup Knob variable's value is always 0 when we reading
  VTIOS setup knob by using gSetupVariableGuid from GetVariable
  in AcpiPlatform file.
  
  [Resolution]

  Restructuring of USB3 IPSD is done to help with standalone IP HW-FW
  Co-Validation. One of the goals was to redesign around features exposed
  by USB3 IP to help with testing on per feature basis.

[SiliconPkg], [BoardPkg]

  Add Code Support for BIOS Guard 2.2 version
  
  [Issue Description] or [Feature Description]
  Refactored BIOS guard IPFW code to accomodate both existing
  BIOS Guard 2.0 and the latest BIOS Guard 2.2 requirements
  
  [Resolution]
  BIOS Guard 2.0
  1. Created a V20 folder to hold BIOS Guard 2.0 structures
  2. Added a new library to allocate new Hash MSR function
  3. Added BIOS Guard prefix and few missing error definitions
  to BIOS Guard module error defines list at BiosGuard.h file
  
  BIOS Guard 2.2 [requires RTL support]
  1. Created V22 folder to hold BIOS Guard 2.2 structures
  2. Implemented Crypto changes for RSA 3072 and SHA384
  Algorithms
  3. Added a new library to allocate new Hash MSR function
  and updates
  4. Updated PKeySlot0 value with SHA384 hash. Set PkeySlot1
  and PkeySlot2 to zero
  5. Added BIOS Guard prefix and few missing error definitions
  to BIOS Guard module error defines list at BiosGuard.h file
  6. Updated BIOS SVN
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg; BoardPkg; PlatSamplePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  LNL, MTL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 14015216803

*********************************************************************************

[BoardPkg]

  MeteorLakeOpenBoardPkg: Remove OpenBoardVpdPcd.dec file
  
  [Issue Description]
  Nested packages (multiple DEC files within a single package) are not
  allowed and EDK II build tool updates are checking for this condition
  and will break builds if nested packages are not eliminated.
  
  [Resolution]
  MeteorLakeOpenBoardPkg contains both OpenBoardPkg.dec and
  OpenBoardVpdPcd.dec files. Merge the contents of
  OpenBoardVpdPcd.dec into OpenBoardPkg.dec and remove the
  OpenBoardVpdPcd.dec file. Update INF files to change references to
  OpenBoardVpdPcd.dec to OpenBoardPkg.dec.
  
  Package/Module: MeteorLakeOpenBoardPkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  All
  
  Hsd-es-id: 22016167395
  Change-Id: I0f48e4010c6ef24d8e8c6a6afd23e7d172ffcbf6
  Original commit hash: c5218570912e2bf410706c42ff853a8385dbdfa8

Commit: e125f61c235c09a7038a453a01cf865a19727733 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  Remove global variable:mConfigTdpBootModeIndex,mCtdpLevelsSupported
  
  [Feature Description]
  Remove global variable in ConfigTDP
  Move CPU PM config to CpuPowerDeliveryConfig
  mConfigTdpBootModeIndex:
  * When Config TDP is not supported, it is not used for hardware
  programming and it's set to 0 which will be saved in HOB.
  * When Config TDP is supported, its inial value is from
  ConfigTdpLevel in a ConfigBlock. It's set to 0 in following cases:
  1. TDP Limit is not programmable (MSR_CE[BIT29] = 0)
  2. Config TDP is disabled (ApplyConfigTdp in ConfigBlock is 0)
  3. it exceeds the supported level
  
  mCtdpLevelsSupported is from MSR_CE[BIT34:33].
  Package/Module:
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/PeiCpuPowerManagementLib
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  C1S
  
  Hsd-es-id: 15012266401
  Change-Id: I160a3b73026315c3aa16f226abe51aa6f4c305fc
  Original commit hash: d40b0067fbd027ca8546279e4f0a8bbd53834094
  
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/CpuPowerManagement/LibraryPrivate/PeiCpuPowerManagementLib/PowerLimits.c

[SiliconPkg]

  Move Boot Guard related defines and CPU_SKU
  
  [Feature Description]
  1. Move Boot guard related header defines to C1S root.
  2. Move CPU_SKU to CpuGenInfo header.
  Rationale: Change in public APIs necessitates the change
  in customer code and more validation to make sure that
  there are no new bugs due to the changes. This also
  discards all the goodness in terms of quality accumulated
  over previous generation's validation cycles. All this leads
  to increase in cost for the customer.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg\LnlCDie,
  ClientOneSiliconPkg\MtlCpu,
  LunarLakePlatSamplePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]

*********************************************************************************


  Fix VTIO default values in BIOS menu
  
  [Issue Description]
  After enabling VTIO in BIOS, defaults values were not getting
  populated. gVtioSetupData was overriding the defaults populated
  by VFR.

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 20a566295d75e2246eba85a2faf174dab014a440 
*********************************************************************************


  [TSE] BlockIoCrypto support for unencrypted IO & custom tweak values.
  
  [Feature Description]
  
  The BlockIoCrypto protocol API defined in the UEFI specification
  describes two parameters for read & write extended operations:
  Index and CryptoIvInput:
  
  1) BIOS will consume the optional Index parameter to determine if
  the operation should be handled by the BlockIoCrypto protocol
  performing inline encryption through the TSE engine or deferred
  to the BlockIo protocol to perform a regular NVMe IO.
  
  2) BIOS should consume the caller's CryptoIvInput as a
  EFI_BLOCK_IO_CRYPTO_IV_INPUT_AES_XTS structure as defined in
  the UEFI spec to determine the tweak value for the AES XTS
  algorithm. This parameter becomes mandatory for the
  BlockIoCrypto protocol supporting TSE.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg, TseFeaturePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  LNL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 14017131738, 14017714845
  Change-Id: I477ddec9b493a77c7aededee19f8950b453d7f26
  Original commit hash: 48d4f2f260db9a4893bafebe7b78b7e8cef9d8ab
  
  Features/Security/TseFeaturePkg/TseNvmExpressDxe/NvmExpressBlockIoCrypto.c
  Features/Security/TseFeaturePkg/TseNvmExpressDxe/NvmExpressPassthru.c

[PlatformPkg]

  CrashLog BIOS knob status is in incorrect
  
  [Issue Description]
  Global reset Trigger mask status reverted back to Modify
  when the global reset trigger masks were set to some value
  other than default settings.

[BoardPkg], [PlatformPkg]

  Support required to retrieve MAC address from PSS chip.
  
  [Feature Description]
  Default MAC Address is read from the Flash region.
  MAC Address is read from PSS Chip.
  New MAC Address is checked with the Default MAC Address.
  Default MAC Address is updated with the New MAC Address.
  Setup option is created in the BIOS Setup Menu.
  It is by default Enabled.
  Upon updating the Default MAC Address with New
  MAC Address the Setup option is the Disabled.
  
  Package/Module: Features/MacUpdate
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTL

[ASL], [BoardPkg], [PlatformPkg]

  Added Lontium + SIO for MTL-PS.
  
  [Feature Description]
  Added Lontium + SIO for MTL-PS.
  
  Control features enablement with newly introduced NVS variables,
  such as I2SE, ITCM, ITHW and ITSI, where they will set to ENABLE
  when PcdEmbeddedEnabled flag is set.
  
  When PcdEmbeddedEnabled flag is NOT set, the NVS variables will
  NOT be set and all the ACPI objects will be hidden.
  
  Package/Module: MTL-PS
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTL-PS RVP, CRB, PPV

[BoardPkg]

  [MTL] Correct the FvSecurity in BiosInfo and ReportFv
  
  [Issue Description]
  BtGAcm would consider the IBB hash get corruption since the
  FvSecurity be reported as IBB which FV locate in OBB.
  This would cause the seamless recovery/resiliency flow get
  failed.
  
  [Resolution]
  - Move the FvSecurity from IBB into POST-IBB in BiosInfo.
  - Remove the FvSecurity report in PreMemory.
  - Add the FvSecurity report in FV list need taken into
  account (or hashed) for the OBB verification.

*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTLP A0] BIOS to resolve TCSS DEVEN based on CAPID disables
  
  [Issue Description]
  BIOS raises an Assert that TBT FW is not loaded and BIOS expected
  TBT FW to load because TBT DMA is enabled in TCSS DEVEN
  TBT DMA should not have reflected as enabled in TCSS DEVEN because
  it is disabled in CAPID (because TCSS TBT is disabled in softstraps).
  The same problem would also happen via port mask softstrap.
  
  [Resolution]
  Note that the bitmap layout between TCSS DEVEN and
  capid0_d_0_0_0_mchbar is aligned.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTLP
  
  Hsd-es-id: 15011945637

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-M MTL-P MTL-S | DDR5 LP5] MRC Data Pi Linearity Monotonic Check
  Error is Fatal
  
  [Issue Description]
  The monotonic check performed in MrcDataPiLinearity results in a fatal
  MRC training error when the input DccCount array includes entries that
  are not monotonic. The MTL MAS spec states that this condition should be
  flagged as a warning, not a fatal error.
  
  [Resolution]
  - Revert "[MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5 LP5] Data PI Linearity - Ignore
  Non-Monotonic Errors".
  This reverts commit 9c659adeca0a02187bd0aa04d79aad9be30a4787
  - Updated MrcDataPiLinearity to ignore the return status of
  MrcMonotonicCheck
  - Added debug prints to MrcMonotonicCheck to display the array values
  checked and flag the non-monotonic entries
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  ALL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 16018041018
  Change-Id: Ie54156ee8c86a6e9aa0ad0fe9f4fba0bb932c35f
  Original commit hash: 51c6c08af5126ffde09a858c96108302b17b2e74

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 251595f73cce254f46e29dd792574551dfafd32f 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-S MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5 LP5] SUT will not boot to OS on debug BIOS
  with Fast Boot
  
  [Issue Description]
  When BIOS Fast Boot is enabled, the platform hangs in PeimMemoryInit
  after a warm reset from OS.
  
  [Root Cause]
  When the reset from OS is performed, the Memory Override Request (MOR)
  bit is set by the OS and PeiMemoryInitLib receives these inputs on the
  Warm Reset exit flow:
  MemConfigNoCrc->CleanMemory = TRUE
  MrcBootMode = bmWarm
  
  When these input conditions are seen, PeiMemoryInitLib triggers a cold
  reset avoid doing the memory scrub operation on a warm reset.
  
  The cold reset fails to complete due to an assert in the ExitBootService
  function which checks if the function was called while the flag
  FastBootFlagStatus is set to 1:
  FastBootFlagStatus BIT0 - 1 -> Fast Boot is still Progress
  FastBootFlagStatus BIT0 - 0 -> Previous Fast Boot successfully completed
  
  [Resolution]
  - Revert "[MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5 LP5][MTL-A0-PO]0055 PC Hang issue Observed
  while resetting system via Reset Button"
  This reverts commit 2e42df6703d7c50161b51d5305389a3ffc652bea.
  - Changed MRC flow to align with ADL implementation where the warm reset
  exit flow is promoted to a fast boot flow when a memory scrub request
  is received on warm boot.
  - When a fast boot is possible but disabled via the MrcFastBoot input
  the fast boot is promoted to a full training cold boot.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  M, P, S
  
  Hsd-es-id: 22015694434
  Change-Id: I96875caf77b00bf34f23a7d3d85d0e4b3dcf99b4
  Original commit hash: 3bc7bf747e72ecd45ee2a21699c24eb22d64c923
  
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl/LibraryPrivate/PeiMemoryInitLib/MemoryInit.c
  

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

  --Commit Message Contains Key Word: revert

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5 LP5] Advance MRC Safe Modes to enable LP5 5600 G4
  
  [Feature Description]
  (1) MRC must enable the following training steps by default:
  LVRAUTOTRIM
  DDRPRECOMP
  RXSALCAL
  DATAPILIN

  (3) MRC must enable CMDVC for DDR5 Gear 4 configs

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 5da9e53df5aa6130e6b036c6982c4b513b80d9f9 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-S | DDR5] R2RMux Trainings updates for MTL-S
  
  [Feature Description]
  With MTL-S supporting 2DPC up to 4 ranks per channel,
  MRC needs to be able to handle all combinations of training:
  1. 2dpc 4 ranks per channel
  MRC should only train dimm0 ranks 0+1
  2. 2dpc dimm0=1rank + dimm1=2 rank.
  MRC should only train dimm1 ranks 2+3
  3. 2dpc dimm0=2ranks + dimm1=1ranks
  MRC should only train dimm0 ranks 0+1
  4. 2dpc both dimms single rank
  MRC should only train dimm0rank0 + dimm1rank2
  5. 1dpc 1 rank
  Training should be bypassed since its not needed.
  
  [Resolution]
  1. Added GetR2RFirstRank and GetR2RLastRank
  to obtain which are the ranks to be run
  2. Change MrcRankExist to depends on RankMask
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg\IpBlock\MemoryInit\Mtl
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  S

Commit: e34cfc75337e8670b8f8f123f525b316b6df1364 
*********************************************************************************

[ASL], [BoardPkg]

  PG3 entry/exit counter verify by ISCT.
  
  [Feature Description]
  1. Expose a UEFI variable to enable disable this feature (will not
  be exposed as a setup option ). By default it will be init as
  disabled.
  2. Using external tool (xmlcli/win api ) to enable it from shell/os
  etc.
  3. BIOS will expose a new ACPI device for ICST (_HID,
  "INTC109B/,EISAID ("PNP0C02 ) only when the support is
  enabled.
  4. BIOS will read Ec offset (0x78 ) to determine PG3 entry exit
  log (BIT2: set to indicate PG3 entered successfully. BIT3: set to
  indicated PG3 exit after counter expiry. )
  5. Will propagate the same info using DSM function 1 in this
  device scope.
  6. Whole flow will be skipped in case the nvram variable is not enabled
  
  Package/Module:EcfeaturePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  Arrow lake - P
  Arrow lake - S
  Metor lake - P
  Metor lake - M
  Metor lake - S
  
  Hsd-es-id: 16017278332
  Change-Id: I330a82f29c1d1310fcc684b70aa889122a148768

*********************************************************************************
Commit: f7e887be3215567929713d1a18b49a5116590158 
*********************************************************************************


  [TSE] Fix PRP references patched by TSE protocol.
  
  [Issue Description]
  
  NvmExpressCryptoPassThru implementation will call
  the TseProtocol's SubmitTseTableEntries() function to
  create the corresponding TSE table entries and patch
  the NVMe command PRP entries before ringing the
  doorbell.
  
  The previous implementation was using a separate variable
  to store the addresses of the PRP1 and PRP2 entries, but missed
  modifying the entries going into the NVMe submission queue.
  
  [Resolution]
  To simplify the code and correct the bug, the implementation will
  now pass the reference to the PRPs directly from the submission
  queue structure.
  
  Package/Module: TseFeaturePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  LNL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 14017330571
  Change-Id: I00c88eb212741f56a2496418c51a19cbec81fd7f
  Original commit hash: 54087c45c4fe9d6ab90ade0d09cdc1551562c5c0
  
  Features/Security/TseFeaturePkg/TseNvmExpressDxe/NvmExpressPassthru.c

[SiliconPkg], [PlatformPkg]

  [MTL-S][OC]Correction added for default values of OC setup variables.
  
  [Issue Description]
  User is not able to enable and save Overclocking feature knob, due to
  Hii Variable failure. And once enabled OverClocking Feature knob in the
  BIOS setup, it is reverting to default disabled value.
  
  [Resolution]
  Fix was added for the OC setup variables default values which were
  getting set to out of valid range value. The input for these variables
  is OC Data Hob which is now created and intialized when OC PCD is
  enabled. Another change is to move OC Pre-mem init call before VR
  pre-mem init call, as VR init is dependent on OC Data hob to know if
  overclocking is enabled or disabled.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg, MeteorLakePlatSamplePkg, LunarLakePlatSamplePkg
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  MTL-S

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-S | DDR5] Search for closest low Freq in ConvertFreq2Clock
  
  [Issue/Feature Description]
  Testing hit DIVIDE 0 error. Outputs Frequency becomes 0.
  
  [Resolution]
  Search freq in ConvertFreq2Clock and choose the closest
  low Freq instead of asking for exact match.
  
  In GetChannelDimmtCK, normalize Ratio when calcuating Clock for
  CUSTOM_PROFILE.
  
  In McFrequencySet, use Outputs->Frequency to get Ratio instead
  of from Inputs->Ratio (CUSTOM_PROFILE1) as it bypasses
  the FreqMax checking and causes unmatch between Frequency and ratio.
  
  In GetChannelDimmNmode, follow XMP3.0 spec to get NMode from SPD XMP
  profile data.

[SiliconPkg], [PlatformPkg]

  [Porting from ADL-S | DDR5 | OC] Add OCSafeMode to control some OverClocking configs
  
  [Issue/Feature Description]
  Some XMP memory modules use very aggressive timing parameters.
  Memory training might fail. MRC uses workaround to tune them, such like
  tCL. However, some special memory modules do work with such aggressive
  configures.
  
  MRC need add a BIOS knob to control it.
  
  [Resolution]
  Add OCSafeMode to control some OverClocking configs.
  When OCSafeMode=1, MRC uses less aggressive configures.
  By default, OCSafeMode=1.
  
  Delete tCLDefault and other timing default variables from SA_SETUP.
  
  Package/Module:
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  ADL-S DDR5 DDR4 OC.
  
  Hsd-es-id: 15011651202

*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-S MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5] Advanced Rx 2D Timing Centering kills Rx eye on 2R configs
  
  [Issue Description]
  Read Voltage Centering 2D training step on 2R systems is causing Rx eye to be incorrect
  
  [Root Cause]
  ChangeMargin function for RdV is programming register with an uncached offset and without
  clearing the offset to 0 before testing subsequent rank, the start of the subsequent rank
  will start off the last tested RdV for previous rank instead of the original RdV that was
  at the start of the training step.
  
  [Resolution]
  Clean out offset to ChangeMargin after the vref sweeps.
  
  Package/Module:
  MemoryInit
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  ALL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 14017049914
  Change-Id: I23e62f979fc89445fef2325dd0775524cd070f79
  Original commit hash: 9ee52aacd4a2a969ba63816a6a2b118f85c5c2d4

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 3a21e7e13d7973e4a29de89e81dde4d8b1744741 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-S MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5 LP5] VCCSA_INTRPOL value in the PMA CR for the current SAGV point is not updated
  
  [Issue Description]
  When MRC is trying to train different SAGV points with the same QCLK ratio,
  PMA HW is supposed to update registers containing QCLK ratio,
  gear and VCCSA value, but it doesn't (stays at reset value).
  
  [Root Cause]
  PCode does not update the VCCSA_INTRPOL value in the PMA CR for the current SAGV point
  when the QCLK RATIO is same as the previous SAGV point.
  
  [Resolution]
  Permanent WA, as MRC is aware of current index QCLK ratio.
  The first time MRC switches to that ratio, pcode will respond back
  with interpolated voltage. MRC will save voltage and for
  the immediate WPs that use the same ratio, it will use the ratio from the first time.
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  All
  
  Registers impacted: MC [ ] Phy [ ] Both [ ]
  
  Hsd-es-id: 22015508755
  Change-Id: I751636f1da0dfc4610bd6fce5fba6a74a7bd72b3
  Original commit hash: 31b9cd27a6968e1211f770c147f3c309b95a3593

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 1e2744c5664917b3ee9949870fb86d82108e38d0 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL][VMD] Revert correction in VMD initialization call sequence due to
  function remapping and add alternative fix
  
  [Issue Description]
  VMD RTD3 ACPI interface uses original B/D/F numbers to map and call the
  respective RP-Index ACPI methods. Since VMD initialization called after
  function remapping in current BIOS flow, B/D/F numbers gets modified if
  RP with function 0 is disabled. This will trigger wrong RP index ACPI
  methods in D3cold flow.
  
  [Resolution]
  1. Reverted the change in which VMD init is called after function
  remapping and moved it back to before function remapping.
  2. For the function enumeration of non-zero functions - modified
  the VMD device discovery flow to continue detecting root port devices
  even if function 0 is not available. That way, VMD setup menu will
  continue to display the original B/D/F number and not the remapped
  function number. In this case it will trigger respective RP-Index
  ACPI methods during D3cold flow.
  
  Package/Module:
  VMD init
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  All
  
  Hsd-es-id: 22015564430
  Change-Id: I7cf78f991ff8762c256bc144f38742d546e7fecb
  Original commit hash: 7bfca52bae0f0993df0920017725e36b0e544cf2
  
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/Fru/MtlSoc/Vmd/LibraryPrivate/PeiVmdInitFruLib/PeiVmdInitFruLib.c
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/Product/MeteorLake/SiInit/Pei/SiInit.c

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 6aa7d65e503e2bedea0f2a37796a1fab895a665e 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5] Blank Display observed while system is in OS with Bios v2313_00
  
  [Issue Description]
  With MRC 0.6.12.2 multiple DDR5 systems exhibit a blank display issue when
  booting into OS.
  
  [Root Cause]
  The issue is not yet root caused but inital triage data shows that the issue
  is not reproducible when either DdrSafeMode or McSafeMode masks are reverted
  to their previous value.
  
  [Resolution]
  Reverted the DdrSafeMode config mask to the pre-MRC 0.6.12.2 value as a
  temporary workaround while the issue is debugged.
  DdrSafeMode = 0x1FF:
  - Enabled bit[0] DDR_SAFE_BASICPM
  - Enabled bit[1] DDR_SAFE_SPINEGATE
  - Enabled bit[2] DDR_SAFE_DCC
  - Enabled bit[3] DDR_SAFE_R2RTRAIN
  - Enabled bit[4] DDR_SAFE_TRANSFORMER
  - Enabled bit[5] DDR_PLL_OPERATION
  - Enabled bit[6] DDR_SAFE_ODT_SENSEAMP
  - Enabled bit[7] DDR_SAFE_VTT_TERMINATION
  - Enabled bit[8] DDR_SAFE_PERIODIC_COMP
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg/MemoryInit/Mtl
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  ALL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 14017199608
  Change-Id: Id46d85759b4dd13a977f89cb523559d8430effd2
  Original commit hash: e95afcf093f8eebe5c561fa985ef209802a2ccbc
  
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl/LibraryPrivate/PeiMemoryInitLib/Source/Api/MrcGeneral.c

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 0c266a98e3e26542e030c305e9f94a716a7e7d32 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg]

  [MTL-M MTL-P | DDR5 LP5][MTL-A0-PO]0055 PC Hang issue Observed while resetting system via Reset Button
  
  [Issue Description]
  A boot hang at post code 0055 is observed when the platform is booted to OS
  and reset using the hardware reset button.
  
  [Root Cause]
  When the system boots up to OS, the OS may set the MemoryOverwiteRequestControl (MOR)
  variable which is a signal to the BIOS to do a memory scrub on the next system reset.
  When the system is reset and the MOR bit is set, the PeimMemoryInit function tries
  to demote the Warm Reset to a Fast Boot flow. This type of boot mode change is not
  supported on MTL.
  
  [Resolution]
  When a MOR memory scrub request is detected during a Warm Reset exit, the PeimMemoryInit
  function triggers a cold reset. The MOR memory scrub request will be serviced as part
  of the cold boot flow.
  
  Package/Module: ClientOneSiliconPkg/MemoryInit/Mtl
  
  [Impacted Platform]
  ALL
  
  Hsd-es-id: 22015559698
  Change-Id: I51e059e89305927def425d787b80f90d0a3228e6
  Original commit hash: 2e42df6703d7c50161b51d5305389a3ffc652bea
  
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/IpBlock/MemoryInit/Mtl/LibraryPrivate/PeiMemoryInitLib/MemoryInit.c

  [Feature Description]

*********************************************************************************
Commit: 56ca9b0566de515ba4d6d315c87510663c25988f 
*********************************************************************************

[SiliconPkg], [BoardPkg]

  [SOC I/O] GPIO Conflict check Failing in BIOS
  - ENUMs changed to UINT32 in GPIOV2_CONFIG structure
  All attributes of this structure have to be of UINT32 type
  instead of enum types due to the fact that enums are casted by default
  to INT32 (signed 32 bit value) and values with MSB bit set
  are misinterpreted by compiler as signed negative values.
  - Removed EndOfPei callback with gpio lock procedure
  from GpioV2PpiInitPei file.
  - Added gpio lock procedure to MtlSocOnEndOfPei function
  to avoid issues with P2SB lock at end of pei event.
  - Updated initial reset configuration for several GPIOs
  - Updated initial TxLock configuration for several GPIOs
  Change-Id: I5746366615dd3b4d1ef9fbe1038050f7a9df5e39
  
  
  ClientOneSiliconPkg/Fru/MtlSoc/LibraryPrivate/PeiMtlSocInitLib/MtlSocEndOfPei.c

[BoardPkg]

  [SOC I/O] Fix for AutoWake from S4
  AutoWake was happening due to _L6F event not being cleared. F20 Wake event being triggered.
  Changing the Input Wake Interrupt Gpio F20(PEG_SLOT_WAKE_R_N) to Inverse Polarity
  for both T3 and T4 LPDDR5 systems.
